     Factory method that always constructs a new {@link IDfSession} object and establishes a new session with the
specified Documentum server.
<p/>
Since DFC 5.1, it is recommended that you use {@link IDfSessionManager#newSession} method instead of this
one.
<p/>
Note that a DFC session created with this method is not shared. Use {@link #getSharedSession} to establish a
shared session with a server.
<p/>
The following code example demonstrates how to obtain an {@link IDfSession} interface to a new DFC session:
<p/>
<HR>Java:<BLOCKQUOTE><PRE>
IDfClient client = DfClient.getLocalClient();
IDfLoginInfo login = new IDfLoginInfo();
login.setUser( "username" );
login.setPassword( "password" );
login.setDomain( null );
IDfSession session = client.newSession(docbaseName, login);
</PRE></BLOCKQUOTE><HR>
@param docbaseName identifies the repository with which you want to establish a session. Specify the name of the
                   repository in one of the following formats:<BR>
<UL>
   <LI> repository
   <LI> repository.documentum_server_name
   <LI> repository@host_name
   <LI> repository.documentum_server_name@host_name
</UL>where
<UL>
   <LI> repository is the name or ID of the repository
   <LI> documentum_server_name is  the name of the server that you want to use
   <LI> host_name is the  name of the machine on which the repository resides
 </UL><BR>
@param loginInfo   An {@link IDfLoginInfo} object that contains the required user validation information.
                   You can pass in null to use the Windows NT Unified Login.<BR>

@return an {@link IDfSession} interface to the new DFC session.

@throws DfException if a server error occurs.
@see IDfClient#getSharedSession
@see IDfSession#disconnect
@see IDfSessionManager#newSession

     This method retrieves an existing shared session if the shared session is created with the same key and the same
repository name and login information. If no existing shared session matches the parameters, a new shared session
will be created and returned. <P> The following code example demonstrates how to obtain an interface to a
non-shared session, then obtain an interface to the shared session:
<p/>
<HR><BLOCKQUOTE><PRE>
IDfClient client = DfClient.getLocalClient();
IDfLoginInfo li = new IDfLoginInfo();
li.setUser("tuser");
li.setPassword("somePass");
// Here's a brand new session.
IDfSession sess1 = client.getSharedSession("docbaseName", li, "uniqueKey");
// Here's a second session shared with sess1.
IDfSession sess2 = client.getSharedSession("docbaseName", li, "uniqueKey");
</PRE></BLOCKQUOTE><HR>

@param docbaseName the repository with which you want to establish a DFC session: Specify the name of the
                   repository in one of the following formats:
    <UL>
      <LI> repository
      <LI> repository.documentum_server_name
      <LI> repository@host_name
      <LI> repository.documentum_server_name@host_name
    </UL>
    where
    <UL>
      <LI> repository is the name or ID of the repository
      <LI> documentum_server_name is the name of the server that you want to use
      <LI> host_name is the name of the machine on which the repository resides
    </UL>
@param loginInfo   an {@link IDfLoginInfo} interface containing the required user validation information. You may
                   leave this parameter empty if you want to use a unified login.  Unified logins are specific to
                   Windows NT.
@param key         an application-defined string. Note that for security purposes, there is no DFC method that
                   returns this key.  You must remember it if you wish to locate and use the shared session
                   created or returned by this method.

@return an {@link IDfSession} interface to the new shared DFC session.

@throws DfException if a server error occurs.
@see IDfClient#newSession
@see IDfSession#disconnect
@see IDfClient#enumSharedSessions
@deprecated use {@link IDfSessionManager} instead for session sharing

     Returns a DFC session that uses an existing DMCL session ID.
<p/>
A DMCL session is a session that is established by a direct call to the DMCL's <CODE>connect</CODE> server
API, or is obtained from an existing DFC {@link IDfSession} object via the method {@link
IDfSession#getDMCLSessionId}. The purpose of this function is to allow an application that already has a DMCL
session to use DFC. In some cases, application developers may decide to call the DMCL directly when migrating
pre-DFC customizations. When possible, however, developers are encouraged to establish sessions through the
DFC.
<p/>
The following code example demonstrates how to obtain an {@link IDfSession} interface by adopting a DMCL
session obtained from another DFC session interface:
<P><HR><BLOCKQUOTE><PRE>
IDfClient client = DfClient.getLocalClient();
IDfSession sess2 = client.adoptDMCLSession(sess1.getDMCLSessionId());
</PRE></BLOCKQUOTE><HR>

@param dmclSessionId the DMCL session ID.
@exception DfException if a server error occurs.
@return an {@link IDfSession} interface to the DMCL session. Note
that you cannot call the {@link IDfSession#disconnect} method on the
returned {@link IDfSession} interface. Use the
<CODE>disconnect</CODE> DMCL server API instead.

@see IDfClient#unadoptDMCLSession
@see IDfSession#isAdopted
@see IDfSession#getDMCLSessionId
@deprecated session adoption is no longer useful without a separate DMCL

     Releases the DFC session created with the {@link #adoptDMCLSession} method.
<p/>
A DMCL session is a session that is established by a direct call to the DMCL's <CODE>connect</CODE> server API,
rather than through the DFC. Note that this method does not disconnect a DMCL session. Sessions established
through the DMCL must also be disconnected through the DMCL with a call to the <CODE>disconnect</CODE> server
API.
<p/>
The following code example demonstrates how to adopt a DMCL session then release the session by unadopting the
DMCL session:
<P><HR><BLOCKQUOTE><PRE>
IDfClient client = DfClient.getLocalClient();
IDfSession sess2 = client.adoptDMCLSession(sess1.getDMCLSessionId());
client.unadoptDMCLSession(sess2.getDMCLSessionId());
if (!sess2.isConnected())
{
// This is what we expect...
}
</PRE></BLOCKQUOTE><HR>

@param dmclSessionId the DMCL session ID

@throws DfException if a server error occurs
@see IDfClient#adoptDMCLSession
@see IDfSession#isAdopted
@deprecated session adoption is no longer useful without a separate DMCL

     Returns an enumeration of all the shared sessions created with a user-specified key.

@param key an application-defined string that identifies the shared session. Note that there is no DFC method
           that returns this key. This is the same string you passed to {@link #getSharedSession}.

@return an {@link Enumeration} object containing all the shared sessions corresponding to the key.
        Will return an empty enumeration if no session is shared using the key passed.

@throws DfException if a server error occurs.
@see IDfClient#getSharedSession
@deprecated use {@link IDfSessionManager} instead for session sharing

     Returns an existing DFC session using a DFC session ID. The purpose of this method is in cases where it may be
desirable to obtain a second {@link IDfSession} instance where both instances share the same underlying session id.
<p/>
The following code example demonstrates how to obtain a second {@link IDfSession} interface from another {@link
IDfSession} interface:
<P><HR><BLOCKQUOTE><PRE>
IDfSession sess2 = client.findSession(sess1.getSessionId());
</PRE></BLOCKQUOTE><HR>

@param sessionId the DFC session ID obtained by calling {@link IDfSession#getSessionId}

@return an {@link IDfSession} interface to the DFC session.

@throws DfException if a server error occurs.
@see IDfSession#getSessionId

     Returns information about the repositories that are known to a connection broker.
<p/>
This method returns an object that contains the repository IDs, repository names, and verbose repository
descriptions.

@throws DfException if a server error occurs
@see IDfClient#getDocbaseMapEx
@see IDfClient#getServerMap
@see IDfClient#getDocbrokerMap

     Returns information about the repositories that are known to a connection broker. Use this function to specify
extended information such as protocol, host name, and port number.
<p/>
This method returns repository IDs, repository names, and verbose repository descriptions. The parameters
uniquely identify the connection broker that responds to this method. If you do not pass any parameters, the
primary connection broker defined in the dmcl.ini file responds. If the primary connection broker is not
available, the request is sent to each backup connection broker in turn, until one responds.  You will receive
error messages for any connection brokers that do not respond. A docbaselocator object contains three attributes that
identify which connection broker responded.
<p/>
Refer to the <I>EMC Documentum Object Reference Manual</I> for more information about 
docbase locator objects and list of protocols to communicate with a connection
broker.  Note that the protocol parameter is null in most cases.

@param protocol   the protocol used to talk to the connection broker (not used in most cases)
@param hostName   the host machine on which the connection broker resides
@param portNumber the port number which the connection broker is using for communications

@return an {@link IDfDocbaseMap} interface to the extended information about the repositories that are known to a
        connection broker

@throws DfException if a server error occurs
@see IDfClient#getDocbaseMap

     Returns information about the connection brokers known to the DFC.

@return information about the connection brokers known by the DFC

@throws DfException if a server error occurs
@see IDfClient#getDocbaseMap
@see IDfClient#getServerMap

     Returns information about the servers that are known to a connection broker.

@param docbaseName the name of the repository associated with the servers for which you are requesting information

@throws DfException if a server error occurs
@see IDfClient#getDocbaseMap
@see IDfClient#getDocbrokerMap

     Returns information about the servers known to a connection broker. Use this method to specify extended
information such as protocol, host name, and port number.
<p/>
The parameters uniquely identify the responding connection broker. If you do not pass any parameters, the primary
connection broker defined in the dmcl.ini file responds. If the primary connection broker is not available, the
request is sent to each backup connection broker, in turn, until a connection broker responds. You will receive
error messages for any connection brokers that do not respond.
<p/>
A docbaselocator object contains three attributes that identify which connection broker responded. Refer to
the <em>EMC Documentum Object Reference Manual</EM> for more information about 
docbase locator objects.

@param docbaseName the name of the repository
@param protocol    the protocol used to talk to the connection broker
@param hostName    the host machine on which the connection broker resides
@param portNumber  the port number which the connection broker is using for communications

@return an {@link IDfDocbaseMap} interface to the extended information about the servers that are known to a
        connection broker

