@throws DfException if a server error occurs

     Queues an archive request to the repository operator.
<p/>
The operator is the person responsible for archiving the requested files.  Documentum provides a utility,
dmarchive, for this purpose. When the operator receives the archive request, dmarchive can be executed to move
the requested file from its storage area to a designated archive area. If you do not specify an operator, the
event is queued to the default operator, who is the user specified in the operator_name attribute of the server's
server config object.
<p/>
Refer to <EM>Server Fundamentals</EM> for more information about archiving and restoring content files.

@param predicate    the object or objects that you want to archive. A valid predicate has the following format:
                    <em>type_name</em> WHERE <em>qualification</EM>. <em>type_name</em> must be a dm_sysobject or
                    a subtype of dm_sysobject, and <em>qualification</EM> must be a valid WHERE clause
                    qualification.
@param operatorName the Documentum user who receives the archive request
@param priority     the priority level of the archive request
@param sendMail     <CODE>true</CODE> if you want the server to send an email notification about the archive
                    request to the user specified with <code>operatorName</code>; <CODE>false</CODE> if not
@param dueDate      an IDfTime interface to the date that the archive request should be completed

@return an IDfId interface to dmi_queue_item, the object ID of the last item queued for archiving; To access the
        IDs of all the objects queued for archiving, run a query against the dm_queue view.

@throws DfException if a server error occurs

     Queues a request to restore a content file or files from the archives.
<p/>
This method queues a DM_RESTORE event containing <code>predicate</code> to the inbox of the repository operator. The
operator is responsible for running the dmarchive utility to restore the requested file or files.
<p/>
Generally, it is not necessary to specify a dump file with the <code>dumpfile</code> parameter. When you archive
an object, the system sets the set_file attribute of the associated content object to the full path of the dump
file.  When you perform a restore, dmarchive reads the set_file attribute to determine which dump file it should
scan for the requested object. Refer to <EM>Server Fundamentals</EM> for more information about archiving
and restoring content files.

@param predicate    the object or objects that you want to restore
@param dumpFile     the dump file containing the archived file. Specify a value only if you do not want dmarchive
                    to search the dump file at the location specified in the set_file attribute
@param operatorName the repository operator. If you do not specify an operator, the event is queued to the default
                    operator, the user specified in the operator_name attribute of the server's server config
                    object.
@param priority     the priority level of the restore request
@param sendMail     <CODE>true</CODE> if you want the server to send an email notification to the specified
                    operator; <CODE>false</CODE> if not
@param dueDate      an IDfTime interface to the date that the restore request should be completed

@return an IDfId interface to dmi_queue_item, the object ID of the last item queued for restoration. To access
        the IDs of all the objects queued for restoration, run a query against the dm_queue view.

@throws DfException if a server error occurs

     Changes a password.

@param oldPasswd the old password
@param newPasswd the new password

@throws DfException if a server error occurs

