     The query (IDfQueryBuilder) attached to this query processor will match only the range of results defined by
the lower bound and the upper bound specified by this method. Several different executions of the same query on
different ranges are then possible just by using this method and then starting again the query either in asynchronous
or synchronous mode
@see #search()
@see #blockingSearch(long timeout)
A method is available to know if range access is supported by the query builder
@see com.documentum.fc.client.search.IDfQueryBuilder#isRangeAccessSupported()
The results can be retrieved using the methods available in IDfQueryProcessor
@see #getResults()
@see #getResults(int from);
@see #getResults(int from, int to);
The indexes specified in the last two methods are local to the result set and don't match the index specified by
the setRange method. e.g. : if a range of 25 results is defined using setRange(26,50), getResults(0,1) returns the
first two results of this bunch of 25 results.
@param lowerBound the range lower bound; -1 is used to disable the range access
@param upperBound the range upper bound; -1 is used to disable the range access
@throws DfSearchException

     Returns the lower bound of the range defined by the method setRange
@see #setRange(int lowerBound, int upperBound)
@return

     Returns the upper bound of the range defined by the method setRange
@see #setRange(int lowerBound, int upperBound)
@return

interface.doc:
   This is a base interface for the query scope.  Scopes are used to provide constraints for the query in a
source-dependent way.  For example, {@link IDfLocationQueryScope} allows you to specify a location within
the source independently from the query expressions.

