      Indicates whether the value stored in the calling value object matches
 the value in a user-supplied value object. <P>

 @param value an interface to the object containing the value that you want to test; Valid
 arguments are <CODE>IDfValue</CODE>, <CODE>IDfID</CODE>, <CODE>IDfTime</CODE>, and the following Java objects: Boolean, Integer, String,
 and Double.
 @return		<CODE>TRUE</CODE> if the values are the same;
				<CODE>FALSE</CODE> if they are not.

interface.doc:
    This interface provides functionality for retrieving values stored in value objects. <P>
 Value objects provide a convenient way to store variant values, which are
 values storing the variant datatype.  The variant datatype is used
 to declare variables that can hold one of many different types of data, as in
 the following example in Visual Basic:
<PRE><CODE>
 DfValue[] vals = new DfValue[num&#95;attrs];
 for (int j = 0; j &lt; num&#95;attrs; j&#43;&#43;)
 {
	vals[j] = myobject.getValue(myobject.getAttr(j).getName());
 }
 </CODE></PRE><P>
 Note that value objects are immutable. Refer to the <em>Docbasic<sup><font size=-2>TM</font></sup>
 User's Guide</em> for more information about the variant datatype.  Refer
 to the <EM>Server Reference Manual</eM> for more information about value
 objects.

